cts, where vowel syncope results in significant pronunciation changes from other Ojibwe dialects.%0a%3c %0a%3c Phonologically, Odawa has a moderately small consonant inventory, with notable sounds being the aspirated [p], [t], and [k]. Morphologically, Odawa could be referred to as highly agglutinative, where a lot of morphological information is encoded in prefixes and suffixes.%0a%3c %0a%3c There are only around 10000 people total that speak Odawa in America and Canada, making it an endangered language. Like many Indigenous languages, Odawa has fallen out of daily use because of English-language influence, and most speakers are older. There do not appear to be efforts for revitalization.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
